 Jurisdiction, and the Execution of Women in Late Medieval France -- t“Je viens …/d’estrange contrée”: Medieval French Comedy Envisions the Afterlife -- tGallows Humor in the Tragicomedia de Calisto y Melibea -- tLate Medieval Carved Cadaver Memorials in England and Wales -- tImages of Mortality in Early English Drama -- tNew Perspectives of the Early Modern Afterlife: The Last Pilgrimage in the Poetry of John Donne and Sir Walter Raleigh -- tMaternal Death and Patriarchal Succession in Renaissance France -- tFear of Seeming Death in Eighteenth-Century Europe -- tContributors -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDeath is not only the final moment of life, it also casts a huge shadow on human society at large. People throughout time have had to cope with death as an existential experience, and this also, of course, in the premodern world. The contributors to the present volume examine the material and spiritual conditions of the culture of death, studying specific buildings and spaces, literary works and art objects, theatrical performances, and medical tracts from the early Middle Ages to the late eighteenth century. Death has always evoked fear, terror, and awe, it has puzzled and troubled people, forcing theologians and philosophers to respond and provide answers for questions that seem to evade real explanations. The more we learn about the culture of death, the more we can comprehend the culture of life. As this volume demonstrates, the approaches to death varied widely, also in the Middle Ages and the early modern age. This volume hence adds a significant number of new facets to the critical examination of this ever-present phenomenon of death, exploring poetic responses to the Black Death, types of execution of a female murderess, death as the springboard for major political changes, and death reflected in morality plays and art.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDeath in art. 0aDeath in literature. 0aDeathxSocial aspectszEuropexHistory. 0aDeathzEuropexReligious aspectsxHistory. 0aMaterial culturezEuropexHistory. 0aMiddle Ages. 4aTod (Motiv). 4aTodesabbildungen. 4aTodeserfahrung. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBaier, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaspar, Cyril L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDanziger, Rosemarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLuca, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFellows, Mary Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolan, Nurit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrubhoffer, Václav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJost, Jean E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Sharon Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPigg, Daniel F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScarborough, Connie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchäfke, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Scott L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurning, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWelch, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g